  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. Global Regulatory Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- International monetary cooperation standards\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate on investigating cross-border financial crimes\n- Extradition treaties\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Anti-money laundering (AML) compliance standards\n- Enhanced due diligence for high-risk jurisdictions\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Asset freezing and seizure\n- Coordinated law enforcement investigations\n- Diplomatic pressure on non-compliant jurisdictions\n\n5. Treaty Obligations\n- Multilateral agreements on financial transparency\n- Standardized legal definitions of money laundering\n- Mutual commitment to combating financial crimes\n\n6. Technology and Information Sharing\n- Interpol databases\n- Digital tracking of financial transactions\n- Cross-border financial intelligence exchange platforms\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
